04401nam a2200637Ia 9781442678200DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20002000onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426782007 a10.3138/97814426782002doi  a(DE-B1597)464728  a(OCoLC)979751148  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPR9220.O35 7aBIO0220002bisacsh04a811/.41 aGerson, Carole, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPaddling Her Own Canoe :bThe Times and Texts of E. Pauline Johnson (Tekahionwake) /cVeronica Strong-Boag, Carole Gerson. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2000] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Gender and History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. 'One of Them': The Politics of Race, the Six Nations, and the Johnson Family -- t2. 'I am a woman': Finding Her Way as a New Woman -- t3. 'Unique figure on the borderland': Literature, Performance, and Reception -- t4. 'The most interesting English poetess now living': Reading Pauline Johnson -- t5. 'Canadian Born': Imagining the Nation -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrequently dismissed as a 'nature poet' and an 'Indian Princess' E. Pauline Johnson (1861-1913) was not only an accomplished thinker and writer but a contentious and passionate personality who 'talked back' to Euro-Canadian culture. Paddling Her Own Canoe is the only major scholarly study that examines Johnson's diverse roles as a First Nations champion, New Woman, serious writer and performer, and Canadian nationalist. A Native advocate of part-Mohawk ancestry, Johnson was also an independent, self-supporting, unmarried woman during the period of first-wave feminism. Her versatile writings range from extraordinarily erotic poetry to polemical statements about the rights of First Nations. Based on thorough research into archival and published sources, this volume probes the meaning of Johnson's energetic career and addresses the complexities of her social, racial, and cultural position. While situating Johnson in the context of turn-of-the-century Canada, the authors also use current feminist and post-colonial perspectives to reframe her contribution. Included is the first full chronology ever compiled of Johnson's writing. Pauline Johnson was an extraordinary woman who crossed the racial and gendered lines of her time, and thereby confounded Canadian society. This study reclaims both her writings and her larger significance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh1 aStrong-Boag, Veronica, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267820040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442678200423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442678200/original  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles